          "body": "Jonathan's speech in verses 4-5 is the most theologically dense moment of this chapter. He does not appeal to Saul's affection for David or to dynastic self-interest (though both are available). He frames the entire matter as a question of *sin* before the LORD — three uses of *chata* in two verses. The argument is structured: David has not sinned against you (negative innocence); David's deeds have been beneficial to you (positive service); the LORD brought about the victory through David (divine attribution); you saw it and rejoiced (your own testimony contradicts the murder plan). Jonathan is doing the work of a prophet — holding a king accountable to covenant standards. His success (Saul relents and swears an oath, v. 6) is temporary, as all negotiations with a heart in rebellion against God tend to be, but it is real. God can use truthful intercession to restrain evil, even when the restraint does not last."
