          "body": "Verse 9 is crucial for understanding Saul's condition: 'an evil spirit from the LORD' comes upon him again. This is the third time the narrator deploys this formula (1 Sam 16:14-15; 18:10; 19:9). The pattern is by now established: Saul's oath (v. 6) is made with a calm heart; David's success (v. 8) triggers the renewed jealousy; the evil spirit descends; the spear flies. The narrator is not excusing Saul's violence by attributing it to a spirit — the moral responsibility for the spear throw is Saul's. But the narrator is insisting that Saul's deterioration is not merely psychological or political. He is a man from whom the Spirit of the LORD has departed (16:14) and upon whom an adversarial spirit now operates, precisely because he has persistently refused obedience. John Owen (Temptation and Sin) would note that habitual sin opens the soul to increasing spiritual disorder; Saul is the canonical illustration."
