        "excerpt": "If you do not save your life tonight, tomorrow you will be put to death.",
        "body": "Michal's episode divides into two parts: the rescue (vv. 11-12) and the deception (vv. 13-17). The rescue is straightforwardly heroic. Saul has surrounded the house; morning means death. Michal issues her husband a survival command — not a request — and then acts: she lowers David from a window, and he escapes. The window-escape is an ancient motif of deliverance in biblical narrative: Rahab lowers the spies from Jericho's wall (Josh 2:15); Paul is lowered in a basket from Damascus (Acts 9:25; 2 Cor 11:33). The structural parallel to Paul in Acts is especially instructive — both the future apostle to the Gentiles and the future king of Israel are preserved by a nighttime window-escape because God intends their work to continue.\n\nThe deception episode (vv. 13-17) is more theologically layered. Michal places the teraphim in the bed — household idols used in the ancient Near East for divination and domestic protection (cf. Gen 31:19, 34; Judg 17:5). Their presence in David's house is unsettling; the narrator does not explain how they got there or why David kept them. What matters for the narrative is that Michal weaponizes them — using objects of false religion as props in the service of preserving the LORD's anointed, a dark irony the narrator clearly relishes. When Saul's messengers come and she says 'he is sick' (v. 14), and when Saul presses and the idol is discovered (v. 16), Michal shifts to outright falsehood (v. 17): 'He said to me, Let me go! Why should I put you to death?' This fabricated threat against herself may have been calculated to deflect Saul's wrath (a king might believe a subordinate could threaten his own daughter) or it may simply be Michal protecting herself. The narrator gives no verdict.\n\nWhat should the student do with Michal's lie? Scripture nowhere commends it, and the case of Rahab (Josh 2) and the Hebrew midwives (Ex 1) shows that God can work through deceptive acts without thereby endorsing the deception as a moral category. Peter Davids (in his commentary on James) and D. A. Carson (on Matthew) both note the biblical pattern: God is sovereign over imperfect instruments, and His blessing of an outcome does not constitute moral endorsement of every means employed to achieve it. The chapter's focus is not on Michal's ethics but on the LORD's preservation of David through her courage.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Teraphim* — plural, household cultic figurines (cf. Hos 3:4, where they are listed alongside legitimate Israelite religious institutions as things Israel will be 'without' during exile, suggesting their widespread use). *Ramah* (deceived, v. 17) — to beguile, defraud; the same root as the name Miriam and as Jacob's deception of Isaac; it implies deliberate cunning rather than an impulsive lie."
